    {
      "id": "40965abc47119464676f5a5289447594b181eaa2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-01-12 21:58:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n(3 comments)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "acc634ca0b6d04b980a386da0ff37bc62c1ae7cb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-01-12 21:59:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nMy suggestion would be to keep \"run_test()\" as-is, but change it to optionally only add tests to the list if e.g. \"$RANDOM_ORDER\" is set, then use \"complete()\" to trigger the test runs if \"$RANDOM_ORDER\" is set and the test list is not empty.\n\nThat would avoid the need to convert all test files manually, and avoid a never-ending series of conflicts as tests are added in new patches and backported to older branches.\n\nThe benefit of making this conditional on \"$RANDOM_ORDER\" is that this can be set on a per-test-script basis with a one-line patch to control how many issues need to be fixed, and it can be set/unset from the test environment as needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
